SW,<br><br>
You had to mention the Parrot's Beak.<br><br>
I was short when the buildup began for **The Great Cambodian Diversion**. I played in the warm-up. A real farce.<br><br>
I would stand by the road and watch all the equipment trundle by, headed west, all part of the BIG SECRET. Portable bridges, arty, engineers, and everything else. Anyone, even the most casual blind observer could see that something big was afoot. Of course, Charlie wasn't supposed to watch. He just peeked a little.<br><br>
It was not surprising that no one was home when the troops came knocking. I suppose they had to do something that resembled a real war, everything else being the total mess that it was.<br><br>
I sat out in a tiny FSB with three 105's for longer than I can really remember a few clicks from the border. There is nothing more frightening than knowing that you had nowhere to protect your back if the gooks came over the wire. We were on intel duty. There were vast sensor fields along the border, and the stuff that was going on behind the scenes was amazing. It was real cute watching the black market and Charlie convoys shuttle over the border, and we just ate our tropical chocolate, scrunched in the bunker, and were never given any orders to do anything. Impotent and surrounded. The great fear of the random and uncertain grim reaper. We had plenty of flechette rounds though. Any gook on the wire would look like ground round after one of those let loose at point blank range. False security. 81mm's would frequently drop in for a visit from the sky.<br><br>
I'm outta here for a while. Sorry folks. I'm too close to going back. Who am I fooling. shit. i'm there.<br><br>
dz 
